text:
this is me. baring it all. sharing the hard truths, the compassionate words, the tears, the unwavering support, all it of.
â€¢
on the screen behind me youâ€™ll see a photoâ€”of me with a woman named buyiswa. i was living and working in south africa doing documentary work with the rape crisis center of cape town. weâ€™re on a stage, very similar to the one iâ€™m standing on before the screen. i took video as buyiswa, a four-time rape survivor shared her story into a microphone, in front of a 300 person audience. again, just as iâ€™m doing on the stage in front of the screen. after buyiswa bravely shared her story of pain and relentless triumph, the microphone was offered to anyone in the audience who wanted to bravely step forward and own their truth out loud. 27. 27 survivors. most of whom had never shared their experiences publicly, if ever. 27 survivors spoke through that microphone, as they not only took back their power, but also came together. buyiswaâ€™s courage was contagious.
â€¢
thatâ€™s what i hope to achieve every time i stand up on a stage and share my truth. i pray before every event that my words meet the hearts of my audience. it doesnâ€™t have to happen from that stage, it can happen years down the road. in those messy, hard, hopeless moments. i pray that my words reverberate in peopleâ€™s hearts, that they bring comfort, hope, courage, empathy and togetherness to all who hear it.

text:
iâ€™ve been in love with tyra banks since about the beginning of time, haha (no seriously though).
every wednesday i honor a woman who perfects her craft while honoring her femininity. 
i love that tyra represents a woman who knows what she is about and what she stands for, i love the fact that she can slay it on the victoriaâ€™s secret runway and had the bravery to launch a show like americaâ€™s next top model and start her own tv show, all completely outside of the  box and yet she wasenâ€™t afraid to take the next stiletto step in her dreams.
:
i think that while you are in a dream itâ€™s hard to even see the next step but tyra once shared that even as a model she was making out a plan of what her next step would be. a woman of success if one who is focused in her present and also has a plan for her future.
:
when her italian modeling agency told her that no one wanted to hire her anymore because of her figure she and her mom went out to a pizzaria and they made a list of all the companies who liked girls with boobs and booty. sports illustrated and victoriaâ€™s secret were on the list. when an industry turned on her, she turned around and with her curves helped to create her own spot in the industry.
:
in life there may be times where people tell you that youâ€™re not needed, or that you donâ€™t fit in. donâ€™t listen gorgeous, just take a step back and redesign yourself in a way that works for and celebrates you. you have your own stiletto spot in your dream and today is the day to step in and own the woman who god created you to be. xoxo. letâ€™s stand together as queens!

text:
visiting garrett-evangelical theological seminary in honor of the victims of japanese military sex slavery in wwii known as â€œcomfort women.â€ japan wanted to bury the history of sex slavery in wwii, but after 50 years of silence, the first survivor broke the silence and spoke publicly about her traumatic story in 1991. the truth came to the surface after the long silence. since then, many women have been following suit, yet still japan is working to silence the voice of the women and control the narratives of history by not revealing historical documents about wwii sex slavery. when i seek to reconcile what has occurred to the korean women, my mentor asked me this question, â€œhow can lamenting about what has happened in the past can lead us into hope for the future?â€ i couldnâ€™t answer it right away, but i came to find the answer:â€tell others the truth.â€ when christians hear the words, truth, justice and reconciliation, many say â€œcanâ€™t we all just get along?â€ their claim to let go of the past and move on tells that they want to seek â€œreconciliation without memory.â€ this approach ignores the wounds and proclaims peace where there is no peace (jer 8:11) this shallow kind of christianity does not take history of trauma and oppression seriously. it abandons the past too quickly in search of a new future. the talk of pursuing reconciliation without facing the truth and justice negatively affects not only the future of communities, but also individual identities. there i hear false prophets continuously echoing in my ear, â€œpeace, peace where there is no peaceâ€ (jer 8:11). christians are marked by the death of christ. we always carry around the marks of christâ€™s wounds and death because christ lives within us (romans 8:10). we carry them with a deeper sense of hope breaking into the world. god created me in korea. god accepted me as his beloved daughter. as a christian and a korean, i will carry the pain and wounds of the women in history with the hope that the voices of the weak, vulnerable, and the oppressed may be heard. 
#metoo
#comfortwomen
#sexslavery
#wwii
#history
#lament
#hope
#christianity

our voices and stories must be heard. 
one in three women experience violence in their lifetime, across all social status, class, race, country or age group. thatâ€™s one too many. for many of them, the #metoo moment hasnâ€™t come yet, because speaking out can have fatal consequences, and survival is a long and complicated journey.
join us on november 22 at the assembly hall lawns for our clothes line project as we recognize the international day for the elimination of violence against women

text:
inclusion and respect towards all people are essential for a more peaceful world. on friday'sÂ #toleranceday, and every day, let's nurture tolerance and respect for diversity - values which bring people together and make us all stronger.

india ğŸ‡®ğŸ‡³, the beloved land of contrasts, teached me a lot about respect for diversity. 
we were just three girls trying to empower a very poor community through women and girls. we knew that some of them (the women) were victims of acid attacks by their husbands and we still wanted to include men on the process.

most of the women and girls had never seen the ocean, never had "fun" or simple pleasures as enjoying pure moments of freedom, creativity and joy... and, for most of them, that's how it was "supposed" to be. some of the men who have attacked their wife's only did it because that's how it was supposed to be. they, the men, were not bad people. i've met some of the most amazing people in india - and yes, men with the sweetest heart. it's not that they didn't want their wifes to have fun or be happy. again, that's how they learned how "to be", just as natural as you learned that it's important to wash your teeth.

to meet in the halfway, to build momentum and make collaboration possible... tolerance and respect were key. no preconceived judgement (and believe me - my activist veins were screaming and almost pumping out of my body for all that making me very angry ğŸ™„).
the truth is, in the end, men were helping girls to believe in themselves, to play without fear, to have fun as free humans, to imagine, to dream and to create. and so, they no longer needed us - they didn't need the western people (!!) to teach them how to be. we just had to empower them to be their true selfs out of an oppressive society (not culture) in which they did not choose to be born.

strengthening tolerance by fostering mutual understanding among cultures and peoples is a precondition for a better future leaving no one behind. â¤ï¸ #act4sdgs #genderequality #womenrights #hearmetoo #timesup #metoo #puri #orissa

inclusion and respect towards all people are essential for a more peaceful world. on friday'sÂ #toleranceday, and every day, let's nurture tolerance and respect for diversity - values which bring people together and make us all stronger.

india ğŸ‡®ğŸ‡³, the beloved land of contrasts, teached me a lot about respect for diversity. 
we were just three girls trying to empower a very poor community through women and girls. we knew that some of them (the women) were victims of acid attacks by their husbands and we still wanted to include men on the process.

most of the women and girls had never seen the ocean, never had "fun" or simple pleasures as enjoying pure moments of freedom, creativity and joy... and, for most of them, that's how it was "supposed" to be. some of the men who have attacked their wife's only did it because that's how it was supposed to be. they, the men, were not bad people. i have met some of the most amazing people in india - and yes, men with the sweetest heart. it is not that they didn't want their wifes to have fun or be happy. again, that's how they learned how "to be", just as natural as you learned that it is important to wash your teeth.

to meet in the halfway, to build momentum and make collaboration possible... tolerance and respect were key. no preconceived judgement (and believe me - my activist veins were screaming and almost pumping out of my body for all that making me very angry ğŸ™„).
the truth is, in the end, men were helping girls to believe in themselves, to play without fear, to have fun as free humans, to imagine, to dream and to create. and so, they no longer needed us - they didn't need the western people (!!) to teach them how to be. we just had to empower them to be their true selfs out of an oppressive society (not culture) in which they did not choose to be born.

text: âœ¨maybe today iâ€™ll wake up different... that was my hope. instead the way the daylight breaks through the window took me right back. and truthfully, yes, i wish i could remember what it was like before it all, but i would not be the person i am today, waking up too early, reading poetry and getting on with life. a gentle reminder this morning, to educate everyone properly to be strong advocates for themselves, as well as for others. to be accountable. to understand boundaries. to practice respect and self-respect. to be vigilant and keep people safe. no stigmatized victimization. itâ€™s time to be fiercely loyal to what is right. it is definitely not easy. accept that because it is time to be honest. it is an extraordinary feeling to fight for your basic human rights, however, i wouldnâ€™t wish that sort of suffering on anyone. strength is absolutely vital. i will not go quietly when it comes to standing up for what i believe is right. #imwithher #metoo #womenforwomen #womensupportingwomen #equality #womenempowerment #womenempoweringwomen

text: yesterday was the first day of national survivors of homicide awareness month. this month runs from november 20th through december 20th. during this time, we will remember victims lost to violence, support the survivors on their journey through grief, and share how homicide impacts loved ones and the community. we know that the holidays can be a difficult time for those who are grieving the empty chair at the table. memories of previous holidays with victims can be healing or difficult or both. over the next month, we will talk about needs of survivors, how we can support them individually and as a community, and give you a little behind-the-scenes look into how access supports survivors.

i am so thrilled to share a project with you all that just came out in this month's elle magazine. this summer i had the great privilege to photograph 11 courageous and inspiring women for elle. this project, titled 'the replacements' is a series of portraits of outstanding women who have taken over the jobs of men who were outed during the #metoo movement. spanning from hollywood to politics and beyond, these women have boldly ascended. as both a woman and a photographer i could not be more proud to have been chosen to shoot this project- i am humbled and inspired. saying thank you to lauren, martin, and katelyn is a huge understatement. you three are nothing short of incredible/ how am i so lucky to work with you?! thank you to all of the amazingly gifted stylists, hair and makeup artists, and assistants who worked so hard on this project. you all are gold. thank you violet o'neill and oliphant studios for your generosity and support.

text:
now this is an important one:

long before #metoo, when i was 10 years old i was molested for 2 years until i was 12 by a family member.  he was 21 and had been raised to disrespect women and treat them like pieces of meat by his father, grandfather and unfortunately great grandfather.  without knowing what i had done, i told my grade 7 guidance counselor about it and immediately it was out of my hands.  an hour later i was in the back of a police car and being taken to station 15 on mariette in ndg (now station 11) in montreal for my statement.  now despite 2 years in court, a bull dog crown prosecutor (she will forever be in my mind and heart), telling 100% the truth, he and his $750/hour (so we were told) defense attorney hired by our family plea bargaining 3 times, he got off scott free.  in fact the last time i ever saw him was shortly after the verdict, driving in a car as the passenger with a bunch of our family laughing like a hyena, looking pretty cool with his arm out the window and right hand on the roof of the car (another image seared into my mind). they couldn't make me out to be the bad one who had solicited him so they went after my mother and defamed her. 
morals of the story: 
1. the justice system is perfect...when it works. 
2. bad guys don't always get brought to justice in this world. 
3. molestation and rape is very real.
4. if a 12 year old girl from one of the toughest backgrounds with no self-image can stand up for what's right and face evil then any of us can do the same. (fyi the crown prosecutor would tell me stories of two and three year olds who had been violated to inspire me to keep going when i didn't want to anymore).
5. i like most police officers: the police officers who picked him up told me that they "misplaced" his paperwork so he had to spend a little more time in lock up.  at least there was that.
6. without law and order this world would be complete chaos.

#molestation #rape #metoo #strong #healed #restored #itsnotonlywomenwhoithappensto #justice #lawandorder #adventurefamily #adventuregirl
name: Lisa Bianca Clarke

text:
an era of darkness :the british empire in india.
by shashi tharoor

about a few weeks ago, while crossing a high risk area on our vessel, we had british armed gaurds onboard, retired members of the royal navy. a recent bollywood movie gold was being played in the smoke room. the movie was about the aspirations of a man to help indian hockey team to win a gold medal in olympics, as they won for british india in past. though the movie was in hindi and the royal navy man hardly had any command over the language, in a span of little time he took to finish a ciggerate he did understand a stange combination of words and that was british india. unable to suppress his desire to enquire about his recent learning he asked "mate, what is british india? ". a man who had served in british royal navy for 23 years had no clue about the 200 long years colonial rule. his knowledge and perception about india was so different that it wasn't even ignorance, it was something that according to him never existed. according to most of his people it never existed. just like germans are in denial of the atrocities of nazi era.  following few weeks, we watched a few documentaries and movies about the british era. a day before his sign off he said " my learnings of this voyage are more scary than the learning of pirate attacks around. i am disgusted to learn about the atrocities and the fact that having served in the royal navy, i had no knowledge of the this part of your rather our history". the oxford debate which i am sure many of us would have watched over internet, had a strong motion. motion of acceptance, if not apology. the compensation paid by the colonial empires are insignificant financially as well as ethically. in context to india it's less than 0.02% of our present day gdp. the repatriation amount considering the time value of money in present day scenario would be an astronomical figure of 3 trillion dollars, that's larger than britain's entire gdp.

i wish there was a #metoo movement for all the colonial victims too. it won't fetch any compensation or penalties but definitely an awareness.

#shashitharoor #amustreadbook #lifeatsea #lifeoffsea #sailorgram

did you know 82% of victims of sexual abuse are females under the age of 18? the effects of sexual abuse play a huge role in the victims mental health. victims are likely to develop symptoms of drug abuse, experience ptsd and more likely to develop depressive episodes as adults. -

join our panel discussion featuring actress @iamarianasanchez as she shares her testimony to give hope and to connect with sexual abuse survivors. at the event she will be offering guidance and resources for counseling not only for survivors but also for family/friends/and significant others of survivors. we aim to talk about the unspoken and break the silence that enables abuse and lack of support.  learn about bold talks that stream from the foundation â€” bold ascension, a campaign that empowers women overcoming adversity. support our movement to spread awareness, tickets available in link in our bio. #theweexpo @latimes @latimesespanol @viaverdecc

text:
bullying, victim blaming, slut shaming, all can lead to suicide. is it worth it?  does a life mean that little to some?  think before name calling, judging, ostracizing, or simply mistreating people.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
stop and ask yourself, if it was my son, my daughter, mother, father, sister, brother, someone i love, someone i care about, being treated this way, how would i feel? â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
sometimes simply listening, understanding, and really â€œgiving a shitâ€ can help save a life.  allowing underwear to be used as evidence to prove consent, is appalling.  this is several steps backwards for humanity.  how many more will attempt or succeed at suicide as a result of bullying (includes slut shaming and victim blaming) before it is recognized that this is a serious matter. â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
donâ€™t let it be someone you love, do your part and be there for those who are struggling, fighting, and need your support.  it starts by listening, caring, and in some cases taking action.  standing up to bullies can include bystander intervention, speaking out, and getting help.  donâ€™t turn a blind eye and simply look the other way.  when you open that eye or turn back around, it simply might be too late.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
as a survivor of a suicide attempt after my sexual assault, this truly hit too close to home for me. these are sad times we live in.  please take notice and do your part. donâ€™t bully, donâ€™t victim blame or slut shame (the practice of criticizing people, especially women and girls, who are perceived to violate expectations of behavior and appearance regarding issues related to sexuality). â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â € â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
help by being part of the solution and not the problem!

text:
i run my fingers over the jagged edges of your soul
trying to lay my hands on the snippets of syllables that creep out every once in a while
i brush the hair off your face
until i'm staring right into your
sultry kohl lined battle-scared eyes

everytime you part your scarlet red puckered lips
i hear battle cries 
they sound of perished dreams 
suffocated by the opinions thrust down your throat 
maybe that's why your voice still quivers 
when you talk about the scars 
tattooed under your eyelids 
streaming down like hot acid 
from lashes smothered in ash
of the flames raging under your skin

i pull you closer everytime you ask me to leave 
for i know somewhere inside this rhapsodic ruin 
hides a girl who longs to be held with the kind of love 
little girls dream about
and unlearn as they grow up 
to find that in the real world 
frogs don't wait to be kissed 
they pounce on you 
tear you apart 
feed themselves with the shards of your dignity 
and tape your mouth with promises of power 
they tell you to get over it 
and you never ask why 
what's the point of opening your mouth
in front of people who can never open their minds

you hand me a piece of blood stained handkerchief 
fingers shivering with philophobia 
i envelop them into my tenderness 
rubbing them clean of the guilt 
society bathed you in

your earl grey eyes meet my copper brown
and i see you don't believe me when i tell you
i can write endless volumes of sacred texts
of the holy grace your smiles leaves behind

you tell me you're too broken to be loved 
and i tell you you're too beautiful not to .
.
. - the luna .
.
.

text:
pre-holiday tip 6....self care is essential....
if your abuser will be attending your family's holiday gathering and you don't want to see them, it's perfectly ok for you not to attend! you don't owe anyone an explanation and you don't need to wrestle with your decision. if you're the parent of a survivor and you know your child's abuser will be present, don't force them to see their abuser, especially if they have made it clear that they don't want to. because, while the holidays and family gatherings are supposed to be happy occasions where fond memories are made, for many, they are the scene of the crime or at the very least, extremely triggering when the survivor is forced to come face to face with their abuser. as a survivor, we encourage you to do what is best for you. and, for parents, do what is best for your child. if that means forgoing your family gathering and creating happy memories with people who love you like family, then do it. self care is essential for healing and we want you want to be an unapologetic champion in your fight to create a space where you find peace, happiness, wholeness and love.  #childsexabuseawareness #stopchildsexabuse #childsexabusesurvivor #parentsofchilldsexabusesurvivor #sexualassault #endchildsexabuse #endrapeculture #childabuse #sextrafficking #atlanta #atl #georgia #women #girls #teens #awareness #sexcrimes #rapevictims #rape #victims #children #prevention #trafficking  #survivor #tips #blogger #speaker #metoo #advocate

text:
a woman's life is filled with changes. she undergoes transition so many times. physically, mentally, emotionally.
for some it's a struggle throughout and for some it's 'easy'. a young girl be becomes a woman, she gets her first period, things change, not only for her but everything about her. people's perceptions about her change. they start to see her, treat her differently. sometimes for the better. they treat her as a young lady as she's supposed to be treated. and sometimes, things get out of hand and we get to witness horrible acts by insane lunatics.
a young woman makes her choices, a student, an entrepreneur, a family, a home-maker, a mother, a caregiver. if she gets the  encouragement and support she needs, she does wonders. she becomes the 'she-e-o' and wins hearts.
but if she's criticized at every step, she becomes empty, hollow, emotionally weak with a meek voice, low confidence with no will to do anything.
a woman, when gets married into a family, she leaves her parents, most of her young-adult life, her siblings, her likes, her dislikes and makes an effort to 'fit' into the family. just to make herself a part of that family, she gives her all. now, if she's appreciated, loved and cared for her efforts and the family meets her half way, she's the most happiest woman with a more happier family, there can be. but if she's treated like a slave who the family brought to cook, clean, take care of them, who's opinion or ideas doesn't matter, then again she lives a lifeless life and she becomes an emotionally drained soul.
now the rest of her life depends on her, how she wants to live.
ladies, make the right choice. take the right turn. be yourself. be confident. your self-esteem, self-respect matters.
do what makes you happy. change is inevitable. but how you deal with these changes is in your hands.
be happy. you and your happiness matters.
.
.
Â©shwetha @shwetha_rishi

text:
for our gratitude camp picture day, i wore my aly raisman style shirt. i am so grateful to have spent nearly 20 years creating a gymnastics programs based on somatic principles of respect and embodied wisdom. and now and so grateful to get to be a part of healing this sport. now, more than ever, people are ready to let in what is important. movement is a development of self. changing the way we teach movement can change the world. kids should be able to get the good with out the bad. they should be able to get more of the good. obviously, it should be a safe space. physically, sexually, and also mentally and emotionally. in the most subtle ways, its the end of an old paradigm where abuse and control were necessary for success. 
gymnastics also builds strength. strength that ultimately over came. i am so grateful for aly (now known for more than incredible tumbling) and so many others who stood up to demand this change. i am so grateful for all the kids though all these years who have grown up with us in a different way. and i am so grateful for the goodness that is yet to come.

sports change the world. thank you to all those using their sport, their body and their voice to stand up for what matters.  #gymnastics #safesport #alyraisman #somaticeducation #somatics #bodypsychotherapy #kids #childdevelopment #embodiment #kidshealth #kidsyoga #kidsclasses #westwood #westla #losangeles #metoo #truth #speakyourtruth #alwaysspeakyourtruth

text:
di kalangan umat islam, wacana emansipasi pertama kali digulirkan oleh syekh muhammad abduh (1849-1905). tokoh reformis mesir ini menekankan pentingnya anak-anak perempuan dan kaum wanita muslimah mendapatkan pendidikan formal di sekolah dan perguruan tinggi, supaya mereka mengerti hak-hak dan tanggungjawabnya sebagai seorang muslimah dalam pembangunan umat. pandangan yang sama dinyatakan juga hasan at turabi dari sudan. menurut beliau, islam mengakui hak2 perempuan di ranah publik, termasuk hak dan kebebasan mengemukakan pendapat,ikut pemilu, berdagang, menghadiri shalat berjamaah ikut ke medan perang dan lain2. ulama lain yang mempunya pandangan kurang lebih sama adalah syekh mahmud syaltut, sayyit qutb, syekh yusuf al qaradhawi dan jamal a. badawi. sudah barang tentu para tokoh ini mendasari pendapatnya pada ayat2 al quran dan hadist.
namun ada juga yang menggunakan pendekatan sekuler liberal, yaitu qasim amin. intelektual yang disebut2 'bapak feminisme arab' ini menulis 2 buku kontroversial, tahriru i mar'ah (kairo, 1899) dan al mar'ah al jadidah (kairo, 1900),dimana ia menyeru emansipasi wanita ala barat. menurut dia, kalau ingin maju buanglah doktrin2 agama yang konon menindas dan membelenggu perempuan seperti perintah berjilbab, poligami, dsb.
gagasan2 qasim amin telah mendapat banyak sanggahan dan ditolak keras. syekh abdul halim muhammad abu syuqqah dalam karya monumentalnya, tahriru i-mar'ah fi ashri r-risalah (kuwait, 1991),misalnya membuktikan bahwa tidak seperti yang sering dituduhkan, agama islam ternyata sangat emansipasipatoris. setelah melakukan studi intensif atas literatur islam klasik, beliau mendapati bahwa kedatangan islam telah menyebabkan terjadinya revolusi gender abad ke 7 masehi. agama samawi terakhir ini justru datang memerdekaan perempuan dari dominasi kultur jahiliyah yang dikenal sangat dzalim dan biadab itu. abu syuqqah juga menemukan bahwa pasca datangnya islam kaum wanita mulai diakui hak2nya sebagai layaknya manusia dan warga negara (bukan sebagai komoditi), terjun dan berperan aktif dalam berbagai sektor, termasuk politik dan militer. kesimpulan senada juga dicapai oleh para peneliti barat. setelah ditelusuri (lanjut komentar)

text:
once in a while
a poem comes my way
smelling of you

its tonality, its texture, its voice
bearing a resemblance
that is nothing short of painful

it pulls me by the collar
and mocks my resistance
as if already aware of
what resistance looks like 
when itâ€™s about to break

i hold nothing back
and get naked 
baring all iâ€™ve got

it will take me tonight
to understand that
the vulnerability of today
comes with 
reluctance of tomorrow

but right now, i neither care
nor understand

for itâ€™s not until 
another day
another poem
another person
when i have to be strong again

and 
a little forgetful.
.
.
animesh ganguly.
(@penningdownthemind)
.
.

questions came upâ€¦â€¦ and i went into study mode. 
i wanted to capture that vibe of the divine forceâ€¦â€¦. energyâ€¦.. the steel within that is in all of us and in everything around us and  relationship with everything around us. our false identities given to us by the objects we consume and surround ourselves with. all material! real??? we are hidden behind our materialist mindset. 
the sandalwood beadsâ€¦â€¦. touch themâ€¦â€¦. the feel and the scent calms the mind. theres a sensualityâ€¦.
sandalwood stimulates the base chakra - believed to enhance trust and self identity. 
the scent of the sandalwood will carry you forward.
this collection follows samark ( connectedness ) and mizu ( water )â€¦â€¦naturally! â€¢asl notebooks, hiva 2018

text:
sometimes when you feel youâ€™re voice and work is compromised by those who are corrupt, itâ€™s hard to find the strength to fight back. after the midterms in florida, i feel myself strangled and bound by the disgusting politicians who have set their missions to destroy the people including myself. i get people judge my need to leave and find something positive to look forward to, they think you should stay and continue working to make it better, but you canâ€™t make something better if youâ€™re not willing to have a revolution. contemporary society is too afraid to actually do something that will help the people. the only way i know how to best bring change as a single being is through awareness with writing, art, music, film, dance, etc. to continue this work effectively, i need to find a place where i can live healthy and sanely. i need to be in a place i can call home, build a career, and feel like okay, i can walk down the street alone today and grab a snack at a coffee shop. no interruptions, no unwanted inappropriate attention. i need a community where my mouth is free to speak.
.
(shut your mouth, self-portrait as marie antoinette, oil on canvas, 2012.) todayâ€™s painting to share with todayâ€™s thought.
.
.
.
.

those who were sexually abused or harassed have used this hashtag.
in response, prosecutions fell in the direction of the victims: â€œthey  provoked them themselves, flirted, dressed too arrogantly!â€

to the question: â€œwhere is the line between Â«arrogantlyÂ» and not so?â€ - the designers answer: â€œthere is no line at all!â€

text:
kepolisianÂ indiaÂ telah mendaftarkan sebuah kasus ke pengadilan yang melibatkan aktorÂ india,Â alok nath.Â alok nathÂ dituntut atas tuduhan pemerkosaan oleh produsernya, vinta nanda. kasusÂ alok nathÂ hanyalah satu dari segelintir kasus yang benar-benar diterima oleh kepolisian sejak munculnya gerakan #metoomovement.

kasus pemerkosaan olehÂ alok nathÂ sebelumnya dibeberkan oleh nanda melalui laman facebooknya pada bulan oktober lalu. nath sendiri membantah tuduhan tersebut dan melayangkan gugatan balasan kepada nanda. ia meminta nanda memohon maaf dan meminta kompensasi simbolis sebesar 1 rupee

tuduhan perkosaan kepadaÂ alok nathÂ tidak hanya dilayangkan oleh nanda, dikabarkan ada dua aktris lainnya yang melayangkan tuduhan serupa.

nanda terlibat dalam suatu proyek bersama nath di tahun 1990, yakni kala mereka mengerjakan serial televisi berjudul tara. nanda mengaku butuh waktu untuk mengumpulkan keberanian selama 19 tahun untuk mengungkapkan apa yang dialaminya.

dalam tulisan di laman facebooknya, nanda tidak menyebut secara spesifik siapa aktor yang ia maksud. ia baru mengakui bahwa yang ia maksud adalahÂ alok nathÂ di kemudian hari.

di sisi lain,Â alok nathÂ mengatakan bahwa ia percaya bahwa pemerkosaan telah terjadi, namun bukan ia pelakunya.

dalam beberapa bulan terakhir gerakan #metoomovement telah membesar, menumbuhkan keberanian bagi para wanita untuk mengungkapkan apa yang mereka alami. gerakan ini menyeret banyak nama, termasuk dari kalangan aktor, jurnalis, komedian, penulis, sutradara, hingga pejabat publik.

tanushree dutta adalah aktris pertama yang melaporkan pelecehan seksual yang ia alami 10 tahun lalu. pelecehan tersebut dilakukan oleh aktor yang menjadi lawan mainnya, nana patekar. sejak saat itu, para wanita memiliki keberanian untuk melaporkan pelecehan dan kekerasan seksual terhadap mereka
.
.source by : akurat .
.

every individual has there own experiences as a child.. someone has good memories and someone has bad/worst. as a parent i discuss with my children about good touch and bad touch, how to be safe and what to be done if something/ someone is bad. 
i would like to ask every parent who read my message to discuss with their children (girl/boy) about good and bad touch. this is the first step to make them understand what is right and wrong. 
i always wanted to support and help children to be mentally strong. so i have chosen my platform to educate children about child abuse and also teach them how to protect them from the abuser.

text:
caged inside her pain
incubating in rage
she awaits transformation 
chrysalis of agony
formed by betrayal 
sealed by lies,
inside she grows stronger.
bars will be broken
scars will be brave
those boots will 
kick the doors down
spine straight
she will walk free.
.
.
poem "pain cage" by t.stark 
artwork by @kamredlawsk .
art originally featured by the incredible gallery page of @she_walks_softly .
.

text:
@richo_kyle our volunteer ambassador /// this year, un women have set #hearmetoo as the theme of this year's 16 day of activism against gender-based violence. i personally, could not have picked a better theme. 
this year, the #metoo movement have inspired many women to start talking about their sexual violence experience. i am eternally in awe of their bravery and am immensely proud to have been able to witness women rise to become more empowered in these recent years. 
now, i aspire to see more changes in the future regarding the empowerment of women. one way to do it is by putting a stop to gender-based violence. whether we like it or not, as of now women is more prone to experiencing violence in their lifetime.
it is time for that to stop.
.
join me @enambelasffest to contribute in the fight against gender-based violence. /// .

text:
nia dinata @ibunia one of our founders ///
we are entering the second edition of 16 film festival in conjunction with #16daysofactivism in the global movement to fight gender based violence. 
we hope to elevate the consciousness level and the courage through our 16 feature and 16 short films in our line up this year.
film adalah media yang ampuh untuk menggambarkan kejadian kejadian dalam masyarakat kita yang kerap bersentuhan dengan kekerasan berbasis gender dan seksualitas. lewat film kita melihat, mendengar, menumbuhkan rasa empati yang tak jarang berujung pada tumbuhnya kekuatan kolektif untuk mencari solusi dan memberantas kekerasan berbasis gender & seksualitas ini.

16 film festival terus berupaya membangun ruang ruang aman untuk berdidkusi, berekspresi, mencurahkan isi hati dan menciptakan support group yang memperkuat kesadaran kemanusiaan. 
meningkatnya angka kekerasan di negri ini memang memprihatinkan. tapi, bukan hal yang tidak mungkin, bahwa kenaikan angka tersebut diakibatkan kesadaran dan keberanian yang tumbuh sehingga setiap kasus meningkatkan kepedulian bersama.

saat ini keberpihakan pada korban lah yang harus diperjuangkan pada aparat dan institusi institusi formil. ruang 16 film festival pun terbuka bagi mereka-mereka yg duduk pada posisi krusial penegakan hukum negri ini.

ayo beranjak, dan turut hadir di 16 film festival! mulai tgl 25 mov -10 desember. besok kita akan jumpa pers dulu di @soulfood.id follow @enambelasffest untuk updatenya. #16filmfestival #zerotolerance #domesticviolence #genderviolence #hearmetoo #metoo #humanrights #womensright #activism #filmfestival #indonesia #komnasperempuan #16haktp #unaids #asv #viuindonesia

so as you lay frozen, you realise, you are in the water. itâ€™s getting darker and darker. you wonder if it really was, that bright and sunny outside anyway. youâ€™re tired. because you know, there are going to be more summers and springs followed by starving autumns and winters. so you decide to let go. like the brave leaf did, silently. no fighting to breathe, no fighting to get back on the land, you just let go. you feel suffocated, but for the first time you know, itâ€™s going to end. the cold water no longer bothers you. it lets you be. you spread your arms embracing death. because life is too long, and youâ€™re too tired to get out of bed.
so why not, let go?
stop fighting for survival. justâ€¦ shut down.

text:
@hood_dinners is a new supper club series, combining sumptuous seasonal food with inspiring female speakers in beautiful locations across london. join them for their next supper club at lcp on friday 23rd november for a conversation on persistence. from activism to politics and the age of me too, female persistence has never felt more important. and so, for their next dinner, come and celebrateÂ three women who have created change - in their own lives and beyond:
*
@disgracecampbell , activist and co-founder of the @pinkprotest . grace will be talking to us about the importance of female activism, organising protests and why she campaigns for change. *
@charlycox1 , poet and mq mental health ambassador. charly will be chatting about raising the awareness of mental health, persisting to improve her own and her new book she must be mad.
*
rebecca armstrong, features editor at i news. almost five years ago, rebecca's husband was hit by a car, changing their lives for ever. since then, she has been 'fighting for him, cheering him up, rolling with the punches and cobbling a life together.' she has written about their journey in a column for the i and will talk to us about her inspring reaction to his accident. 
come for three delicious courses, amazing cocktails and inspiring chat from three brilliant women
.
.
.
.
.

text:
@meetingofmindsuk with a clear lines event:Â writing about trauma, recovery & gender-based violence -Â thursday 29th november 2018, 6:30 pm @ waterstones, 82 gower street, london wc1e 6eq

to recognise the un womenâ€™s '16 days of activism against gender-based violence', we will be hosting this special clear lines event, bringing together women authors whose work addresses issues of sexual violence and consent. often drawing from their own lived experience, these award-winning writers work across a range of fiction, poetry, non-fiction, and memoir to capture the human truths behind trauma and challenge the injustice of gender-based violence.

join us for a lively, honest discussion that will be divided into two panels of authors. what ethical considerations must a survivor/writer take on board when addressing this subject matter? is creating literature from trauma triggering or healing? what challenges do we face from the publishing industry, and how may this have changed in the wake of #metoo?

contributing to this discussion will be winnie m li (dark chapter, winner of not the booker prize), louise beech (maria in the moon), clare shaw (head on and flood), madeleine black (unbroken), abigail tarttelin (dead girls), and clare best (the missing list). winnie and poet-playwright tanaka mhishi will chair.

clear lines is the ukâ€™s first-ever festival dedicated to addressing sexual assault and consent through the arts and discussion. it is entirely volunteer-run and seeks to replace shame and silence with insight, understanding and community. 
tickets are Â£8 (Â£6 for students) available from eventbrite.

text:
hot news
preity zinta tulis surat terbuka, meminta maaf telah menyakiti perasaan orang terkait me too ğŸ˜¯

preity zinta, yang telah menerima reaksi balik untuk pandangannya tentang gerakan #metoo, merilis pernyataannya tentang gerakan itu dan meminta maaf karena tidak sengaja melukai perasaan orang.

dalam pernyataannya, bintang 'kal ho naa ho' ini berkata, â€œsaya pendukung besar gerakan ini dan sangat disayangkan bahwa beberapa komentar saya diambil di luar konteks. saya mengakui bahwa setiap orang berada dalam posisi untuk melawan dan saya tidak ingin mengesampingkan para wanita yang telah dilecehkan". mengacu pada pengalaman #metoo-nya sendiri, preity mengatakan bahwa itu juga terjadi padanya dan dia bereaksi dengan kuat. "alasan saya mengatakan ini 'saya berharap sesuatu seperti ini akan terjadi pada saya, saya akan bereaksi terhadapnya dan banyak lapisan, ketika itu terjadi, saya bereaksi dan seluruh dunia melihatnya", katanya.

gerakan #metoo, yang dimulai di hollywood lebih dari setahun yang lalu, kini digerakkan di india setelah mantan aktris tanushree dutta menuduh bintang mainnya, nana patekar diduga melecehkan dia di set lokasi syuting 'horn ok pleassss' pada tahun 2008.

sejak itu, para wanita dari berbagai lapisan masyarakat, terutama media dan industri hiburan, telah menyamakan dugaan pelanggaran seksual terhadap subhash ghai, alok nath, vikas bahl, kailash kher, chetan bhagat, sajid khan, dan varun grover, diantara yang lain bahkan saat mereka semua membantah tuduhan itu.

preity zinta selanjutnya akan terlihat dalam film tundanya, bhaiaji superhittt. film yang juga dibintangi sunny deol dan ameesha patel ini akan rilis jumat ini. ğŸ˜‰

for all it's worth, it's in the past. i have moved ahead. i haven't forgotten. i never will. but nonetheless, i am not going to let it pull me down. i am going to step on it, and rise. the fear, the insecurities, day by day, month by month, year by year, no matter how much time it takes, i'll make it fade away. and it will fade away. .
.

text:
// know- know not//
.
i know not where safety resides
i know not the faces in disguise
i know not the monsters with a grin 
i know not how many of them win
i know only the shouts of blame 
i know only the cries of shame
i know only that i was alone
i know only that i was alone

i know not why those eyes were full of pity when i walked past them 
i know not why they turned away when i spoke to them
i know not why i stopped myself
i know not why i blamed myself

i know only that i have to heal
i know only courage and strength
i know only that i have to fight
i know only that i am alone
i know only that i am alone 
i know not how to hide 
i know not how to survive
i know not why i am alone 
i know not why i am alone

i know only to colour my canvas with hues of justice 
i know only support and love
i know only to stand by us
i know only to stand by us
.
.

text:
ok lovely.  grab a cup of tea or a glass of wine and let's chat about how you're blocking your manifesting.  because, let's face it.  you are the only one in the way.  #ohdear ğŸ¤¦â€â™€ï¸
there are 4 main blocks that cause most mum's to become "stuck" and to give up on manifesting.  but before i share them, let me just give you a heads up. you're always manifesting.  it's just whether you're doing it consciously or unconsciously.  so, with that part out of the way.  let me share those pesky blocks with you so you can learn what's keeping your manifestations at arms length and allowing the sh$t to show up in your life more than the blessings #oratleastthatshowitfeels #alessonorablessing 
1. worry ğŸ˜©- hello my old friend.  this is by far the most common block and i know you're partaking in your fair share of it.  worry comes in many flavours. from worrying about the how it will happen, to the when it will happen and finally to the where it will all unfold.  worry is basically your way of giving the universe the middle finger and telling it to send your dreams to someone else.  my advice: detach from the outcome. what is there to worry about when youâ€™re not emotionally attached?
2. fear ğŸ¥º- this is the most irrational of all the blocks, because really! unless your life is in danger, what is there really to be scared about?  shame our brain doesn't know the difference.  get used to fear because she ain't going anywhere and the sooner you learn to befriend her, the sooner some pretty cool stuff will show up in your life.  my advice: pull fear in close and tell her it's time to take a backseat in your life.
3. distrust ğŸ˜’- whether it be in yourself, others or the universe.  not having complete an utter faith is a sure fire way to keep an outcome from showing up in your life. faith is the secret manifesting sauce and a must in any manifesting formula. my advice: treat your manifesting as an experiment and allow whatever outcome to guide you towards the lesson you need to learn. 
4. impatience ğŸ˜–- this is huge! enormous and a challenge of monumental proportions for so many. weâ€™re all in a rush #metoo to create our dream life, to have it all and to then what? cont in comments

text:
to another year that's gonna end soon ,
dear 2018 ,
this year has taught me that life can be kind ,unpredictable ,chaotic yet beautiful .

that i don't need to have everything figured out what happens next and that things will happen eventually when i don't stress much over it .
there will be days when my sadness consumes me but there will be days when i laugh so much that my stomach hurts .

this year has given me friends and people that i now fear loosing.this year has been an year of breakups and heartbreaks and realizations .
that life is indeed beautiful and the realisation that you are living one more day makes it special .

things that happened in 2018 that i am going to remember :- â€¢the year we lost stan lee and his cameos and parts if our childhood and marvellous memories that we can never assign to oblivion . â€¢ the year we lost sridevi and the lady of golden era of movie and the woman that taught me the word 'judgemental ' and how you don't have a lifetime because maybe death comes unannounced when you are happy and with your family . â€¢ the year netflix gave us binge watching worthy shows like sacred games and characters like bunty and gaitonde and why an umbrella and bhagwan have different meaning now . â€¢ the year of the second wave of #metoo movement in india and how the horrors left us traumatised . â€¢the year of avengers infinity war . â€¢the year of fifa world cup and it's unexpected turns and winners. â€¢ the year of some beautiful songs . â€¢the tragedy of kerela floods and the mass destruction in god's own country . â€¢ the year of beautiful weddings like deepveer and the royal wedding that restores our faith that maybe there is love after all . â€¢the year if scraping of section 377 and the victory that love triumphs in the end . â€¢ the year the melting stories reached 126 k .(shameless self promotion .like .share .comment guys .) to the year of sad departures ,tears and our inability to let go.

to many more beautiful moments and things to come in years ,to the hope that life is worth living and that nothing can be to messed up that cannot be fixed with a cup of chai and kpop song .

to the year that made me feel more human and flawed .

text:
eeyore was always my favorite when i watched winnie pooh. because i understand him. but what i loved even more was that his friends always cared about him and loved him and invited him although he was sad all the time.
friendship. all my life i always thought i made great friends in school. i always helped them when they needed help, i let them copy my homework and i really thought we're great friends. but when i needed help no one was there. when i forgot to do my homework no one let me copy theirs. they we're just friends with me because it was beneficial for them. we made thousands of selfies together, but no one ever posted them somewhere online and one day i heard one of my 'friends' say "i would never post a picture with her, i mean look at her and look at me" behind my back. that's why i have trust issues. i never heard anything from them after finishing school, one of my 'friends' even blocked me everywhere after i wrote her a message. 
and during my depression i had no one. everyone ignored me. i was completely alone when i just needed at least one friend. i really thought i would never find friends who like me for me.
since 2012 i know what real friendship is like when i met one of my best friends today. she really liked me for me. we helped each other and we were there for each other. and we're still friends which makes this my longest friendship.
and last year i got to know a completely different kind of friendship when i met some of the best people i know in london because adele cancelled her concert. we were a group with people from so many different countries and we just had fun together without any prejudice. some people of this group really changed my life and i'm so thankful to have them in my life.
so if you feel alone right now and you don't have any friends, i know how you feel, i've been there. but you'll find true friends as well. â™¡
.
.

text:
what form does religion or belief discrimination take in the workplace?
direct discrimination can occur at any stage of employment â€“ from refusal to make an offer of employment at the recruitment stage, to inequality in pay and benefits compared to other colleagues, reduced or lack of opportunities for training and promotion, changes in employment terms or responsibilities of role, to redundancy and dismissal.
there are three types of direct discrimination to be aware of:
when an employee is unfairly treated by their employer due to their religion or belief, or lack of religion or belief
when an employee is treated unfairly because of their perceived religion or belief
when an employee is treated unfairly because of the religion or belief of a friend or family member â€“ known as discrimination by association.
indirect discrimination
this often involves the introduction of or amendment to workplace policies and procedures that unfairly disadvantages an employee of a religion or belief. for example, the requirement for all staff to work one weekend a month may conflict with a personâ€™s religious beliefs.  #gurls #workplace #woman #entrepreneur #femaleentrepreneur

text:
we celebrate you our dear @hettycoconutworld on the successful hosting of the coconut festival!
@hettycoconutworld is part of awlo's ngfl fellowship.
.
"my dream of hosting coconut festival finally came true. 
this didn't happen without challenges. at a point,  i asked myself what's the point of doing this?  thank god for family and friends who believed in the dream and kept encouraging me. 
rejections everywhere. it looked like my dream was strange and yes, it was strange to some people. it was as if my dream has never existed, i got it from planet mars. 
these rejections got a part of me though but god saw me through. 
at the end, coconut festival was a success. 
i want to sincerely appreciate everyone that  supported my dream. you all made this possible.  thank you so much for everything." - #thecoconutprof
#raisingthenextgeneration #nurturingdreams

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
letâ€™s talk about consent. 
i went on a date the other night, and everything was going fine. until it wasnâ€™t. the guy that i met in a dating app asked me to go to dinner, so i said yes. we met at a bar, and started talking. then things got weird. he was asking me very pointed questions, wanted to know if i lived alone, if i lived down here with anyone, or if my family was here. he then kept on redirecting the conversation to money. i got this terrible feeling in the pit of my stomach, and thought to myself, you need to get out of there. so, i excused myself to the bathroom, and went and washed my hands, while i decided what to do. lucky for me, i had already had a headache going into that night, so i ran with it. i went back to the table, went to take a drink of my water, and my mind said not to. that horrible feeling got worse. he then walked me to my car, after asking me back to his place a few times, to which i declined. at my car, he kept on pressuring me to go back to his apartment, even though i had said no. and i had said iâ€™m not feeling well, and need to go home. then, he kissed me, and i again said â€œno, i need to go. donâ€™tâ€. at this point, i felt so sick to my stomach that i was shaking. i needed to get out of there. i then went to leave, when i noticed he was following me, and i ended up taking a couple of turns, stopping in a parking lot, and then kept going (all while he was behind me) and lost him on the tollway. 
the point of this, is to illustrate a simple point. if someone says no, they mean it. i donâ€™t care if youâ€™re my husband, my girlfriend, or the pope. you do not lay your hands on someone or kiss them unless they say itâ€™s okay. consent is a problem in this country, and while i was safe and i got out of the situation this time, it isnâ€™t always the case. and once upon a time, that wasnâ€™t the case for me. so. if you wouldnâ€™t be okay with it happening to you without permission, donâ€™t do it to someone else. #nomeansno #consent #metoo

i find that thereâ€™s such a weird stigma around therapy. people think that your life has to be a mess in order to go. thatâ€™s is 100% bs. itâ€™s like when you fall over and hurt yourself. you donâ€™t just sit around waiting for the pain to stop, you take yourself to the doctor. your mind has slip ups as well and sometimes it needs the doctor to came in and give you exercises to stop the pain and recover. 
i follow my mums foot steps, she did a lot of aromatherapy, talk therapy and meditation when i was younger. i guess itâ€™s always been pretty normalised in my family. ive used a range of different types of therapy with lots of different therapist this year, iâ€™ve also used my own mindfulness through creativity and being in nature. everyone is different. i started hypnosis, to deal with self love, which i think is amazing, and talk therapy as well as yoga, guided mediations and staying pretty active. i reckon we cut the bs of having to be broken to receive help. even if youâ€™re stressed at uni or school or feeling a little lost. talking is such an incredibly powerful tool and can have such a powerful impact, there is no judgement in reaching out when it all feels like itâ€™s a bit too much.  xx 
also if you have experienced significant trauma, i might just mention that heading to your local gp allows you access to therapy and victim support. the doctor will give you a certain amount of sessions from whom ever you feel comfortable with. they will be subsidised depending on the government etc. 
#offmychest #metoo #wecandobetter #takealoadoff

'why didn't you say earlier?' text:
the last few days have been really empowering but also exhausting. i had been talking about pressing charges for a while with my therapist. i felt like i had a responsibility for myself and for other women to go through with it. he had managed to isolate me from all of my friends, family and now heâ€™s isolated me from my own country. i felt like heâ€™d won. he got what he wanted all along and that was my silence. 
this week i made the decision to head to the police. being in australia it meant the process is longer and more complicated. i got turned down from the police station in brisbane, nz came to the rescue. thankfully, i was with my therapist and i wasnâ€™t on my own. this is why women donâ€™t report things. this was the reason. because you get judged, no matter who you talk to or who you tell. it felt like my safety wasnâ€™t important. it was no longer his control, iâ€™d taken the wheel. a weight was lift off my heart. iâ€™ve got a bloody big fight ahead of me. iâ€™ve never felt more empowered and i never felt like my voice has matter as much as it does now. never take no for an answer when something like this happens. your voice, your safety is far more important than anything or anyone else. no matter how complicated the situation is. your life matters. xx #yourlifematters  #metoo #femaleempowerment

text:
the process of taking my statement was full on, i donâ€™t think i was reliving it as severely as iâ€™d excepted myself too. the flashbacks felt more controlled as they were being told to someone that could make a difference. the detective then explained the next steps which are going to be a slow painful process. i am and will be forever grateful to have rosie by my side, as upsetting as it was for her to hear, telling my story was less of a challenge with her in the interview room.

i am learning a lot about myself, learning the amount of patience, love, forgiveness and loyalty i have. how to spot red flags really early on. things that i have previously in my past missed. as much as i want to be empowering other wahine to be brave. i donâ€™t feel like a brave or strong. i donâ€™t feel empowered, i feel incredibly heavy. i am still in a state of shock that the person whom i loved could put me through that much pain.

the one thing i took away the most from this weekend is the power and strength of friendships. you can never be isolated from those that love you the most. friends like rosie will leave a room and still manage to make your stomach hurt from laughing, that will sigh as loudly as you do walking home because no words can explain the feeling. thereâ€™s always someone to share a smile with when all you can see is black, and those people are so incredibly precious to surround yourself around. #backtobrissy #metoo #offmychest

holidays can be particularly difficult when it comes to being taken advantage of by family members or family friends. for a lot of people who identify with the #metoo movement, inappropriate touching, patterns of molestation, and other incidents of abuse & harrassment happen during the holidays & at family gatherings. and many times, the reason victims & survivors don't report is because the embarrassment & stigma of such a family scandal is too much to face and they end up with no support system at home or anyone they can trust to believe them.

it's not always easy, but here are some uncomplicated & positive ways to be supportive & helpful if someone confides in you about something that made them uncomfortable or doesn't seem right.

a lot of painful poetry comes from being abused & harrassed. it's a a lot more common than one might think. don't tell them it was just a joke. don't tell them they must've misunderstood. don't tell them to stop flattering themselves. don't tell them so&so is just drunk & didn't mean anything. don't tell them to lighten up because it's the holidays. don't tell them that's "just the way he is..." #timesup on that.
.
#vomopo #thanksgiving #takebackthenight #protection #family #shepersisted #helpdonthurt  #suicideprevention #harassment #abuse

text:
a clear lines event:Â writing about trauma, recovery & gender-based violence -Â thursday 29th november 2018, 6:30 pm @ waterstones, 82 gower street, london wc1e 6eq

to recognise the un womenâ€™s '16 days of activism against gender-based violence', we will be hosting this special clear lines event, bringing together women authors whose work addresses issues of sexual violence and consent. often drawing from their own lived experience, these award-winning writers work across a range of fiction, poetry, non-fiction, and memoir to capture the human truths behind trauma and challenge the injustice of gender-based violence.

join us for a lively, honest discussion that will be divided into two panels of authors. what ethical considerations must a survivor/writer take on board when addressing this subject matter? is creating literature from trauma triggering or healing? what challenges do we face from the publishing industry, and how may this have changed in the wake of #metoo?

contributing to this discussion will be winnie m li (dark chapter, winner of not the booker prize), louise beech (maria in the moon), clare shaw (head on and flood), madeleine black (unbroken), abigail tarttelin (dead girls), and clare best (the missing list). winnie and poet-playwright tanaka mhishi will chair.

clear lines is the ukâ€™s first-ever festival dedicated to addressing sexual assault and consent through the arts and discussion. it is entirely volunteer-run and seeks to replace shame and silence with insight, understanding and community. 
tickets are Â£8 (Â£6 for students) available from eventbrite.

text:
i faced a demon today. my soon to be not stepdad. i was hopeful it would be over today but he refused to settle with my mother for the dissolution of their 12-year marriage. 
we went through security at the courthouse and with my husband by my side, made it to the 4th floor.  the instant the doors open, in the hallway, there he sat on a bench, looking straight ahead. he locked eyes with me and i could see the panic and recognition overcome his face. fear flashed across his eyes as his pupils dilated. 
you see, it is the first time i've seen him since i told my mother the truth, that when i was a teenager, her husband raped me between the ages of 16-19. 
walking up the stairs into the courtroom my stomach felt like an entanglement of a thousand different feelings, most coming to the same conclusion of "i don't want to be here." as soon as i saw him, i smiled the biggest smile i could. i thought i would just fake it and do it to show a brave face. my smile was not fake, i smiled so big, so genuinely at him, you could physically see him become agitated and he started "air drumming" at a quicker pace with his feet than he was before. 
this demon no longer has any power. he can't and won't hurt me again. i won't let him. i'm no longer a depressed, outcasted nerd who can be taken advantage of. i am a grown woman. i may not get my justice, but if my mom is taken care of, i've already won. 
as i am positive, i am not the only person he abused, i currently have an official police report with the clark county sheriff's department and will gladly testify at any point against him. i've grown, and become stronger. my demons won't ever win again. #demons #facingmydemons
#metoo #strongerthanyou #ptsd #growthroughwhatyougothrough

text:
my wonderful friend and colleague @erica.sha and i recently held a lecture about badass women who have influenced (and continue to influence) the coffee industry at @losangelescoffeefestival. i was blown away by the support from those who attended. we wanted to highlight some important women who are often overlooked, though they have helped to make our industry what it is today. we also talked about the importance of inclusivity and diversity in the workplace. 
this last saturday, i also had the chance to host and moderate a â€œwomen in coffeeâ€ panel. thanks to @moderntimescafe and @juniorhighla for this opportunity. we talked about our goals and what inspires us, as well as issues that women often face at work and what we would like to see happen in order to fix those issues. we lifted one another up and learned from each other. i want to see more of this. 
we should not be afraid to speak out and have conversations about sexism, racism, homophobia, transphobia, ageism, or sexual harassment. the way to a solution is never to ignore the problem, but to discuss and find solutions. we need to find allies in one another, to find comfort and support within our communities. i am so grateful for the platform i have to speak on these issues, and with that said, the coffee industry is not immune. itâ€™s much more inclusive than other industries in a lot of ways, but is certainly not perfect. only together can we make it better.

text: iâ€™ve been cranking out these leaves lately. as iâ€™ve been thinking about what i want @bossladycreates to become, iâ€™ve been considering the quote i discussed a few weeks ago: â€œthey tried to bury us, they didnâ€™t know we were seeds.â€ i have interacted with so many survivors who feel buried. silenced. like they donâ€™t have any power or agency over their own stories anymore. itâ€™s a terrifying, truly suffocating feeling. but when you realize that the thing that has been buried is actually a seed has been sown, you give it the opportunity to grow- and to transform into something bigger than it ever was to begin with. as i have shared @bossladycreates with friends and family, i have heard other survivors express this desire- this need- to grow from these horrific experiences. so i have been distributing these leaves to survivors who wish to share their stories and to collectively root themselves in this beautiful community that has been taking shape. they will write their stories on these leaves, and iâ€™m going to grow them into a survivor tree. all of our stories and voices together can create something that will bring us strength and shelter. we will not stay buried. âœ¨ğŸŒ± #survivor #survivoradvocate #believesurvivors #believewomen #metoo #endrapeculture #artist #wip #thesurvivortreeproject

text:
i realize i might lose friends over this essay. there will be many who will not understandâ€“ particularly of my generation. millennials, for all the intelligence at their fingertips, are surprisingly unappreciative of subtlety, real honesty, or disagreements with their social actions/activity. but, i have made a vow to be honest in my writing. when i wrote plays, i could rarely be in the audience with them as it was like i was ripping open veins and letting the audience watch. as tough an image as this is, it is healthy for a writer to take pains to never lie.

text:
empathyÂ has manyÂ benefits. 
first, it feels really good. 
the pleasure centers of the brain light up when weÂ protect and care for another living being. it reduces stress and fosters resilience, trust, healing, personal growth, creativity, learning and nourishing connection. 
when we have direct contact with an animal we often anthropomorphize them. there is good reason for this, we see them as vulnerable, in need of love and care, capable of love and nurture. we were born with this ability not born to destroy. 
if we allow our conciousness to be in the position of others we are thinking at a higher level. collectively focused on preservation enables survival.

this planet is full of symbiosis and if we destroy it so do we destroy ourselves.

text: today is transgender day of remembrance. today we honor and remember the lives of those savagely lost due to transphobia. according to the human rights campaign, there have been 22 reported violent homicides against transgender individuals in 2018. in 1999, gwendolyn smith founded transgender day of remembrance to honor the murder of rita hester, a transgender woman in massachusetts. as scholar and advocate for transgender individuals, sarah lamble states, â€œour task is to move from sympathy to responsibility, from complicity to reflexivity, from witnessing to action. it is not enough to simply honor the memory of the deadâ€”we must transform the practices of the living.â€ violence does not discriminate and neither do we in who we provide support to. access supports all survivors and victims of violence. please take a moment of silence honoring lives lost with us today. #tdor

text:
on today's podcast episode of the @pleasurerisingpodcast i chat with lisa foster from parillumeâ„¢ about sexual violation. .
in particular we discuss reclaiming who you are, healing and thriving after sexual violation.
.
we chat about her story of sexual violation, and i even open the doors for the first time on my own personal story with sexual violation. it is scary to sometimes share things which are so personal, but i am hoping this episode will open up the conversation even further - even if it's just a conversation we have with ourselves. .
lastly, we explore power plays at work, as well as what happens when you know the person who sexually violated you. 
and as always we close we three pleasure questions - what's your fav sex toy, what are you reading and what are you listening to right now. .
c'mon over to itunes and type in pleasure rising podcast to tune in to the show.

text:
as you prepare for your long car rides over the holiday weekend, add these 6 podcasts that will change how you think about your leadership journey to your podcast queue.
.
podcasts are a way of life for meâ€”they are both a pathway to dive deeper into the insights, ideas, and connections of my favorite topics, and an escape from my constantly-curious mind, a ticket to another world.
.
iâ€™ve listened to quite a few, and this is my roundup of the most practical and impactful episodes on leadership.
.
1. women at work. start with: make yourself heard. three female editors talk with guest experts about strategies that go beyond "speak up more," ways to assertively communicate your ideas in a meeting, and practical examples of how to confront someone who chronically interrupts you.
.
2. hidden brain. start with: â€œwhy now?â€. this episode explores the #metoo movement through the lens of the social sciences and will change how you think about being a woman in the office in 2018.
.
3. ask a manager. a call-in work advice show with practical, applicable ideas and language that you can apply in your everyday work. start with: iâ€™m bad at taking feedback.
.
4. how i built this with guy raz. start with: drybar with alli webb. for when youâ€™re curious about how to scale a business idea, listen to these stories behind some of the world's best-known companies.
.
5. dear hbr. start with: bad bosses. a research-based advice show for when youâ€™re deciding whether to report a bad boss, flee, or find a way to stay and work together.
.
6. startup. start with: running a family and a business. for when youâ€™re juggling career ambition with being there for your family. .
bonus: modern love. start with: one bouquet of fleeting beauty. because sometimes you need a break from thinking about work and leadership, and modern love is just the salve for your soul.
.
check out the roundup and episode descriptions on the women in leadership nexus blog - via link in bio.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
mgtow 101: how the dark side man thinks

i want to make it known that when i speak about dark side lovers, i'm usually speaking about the dark side sexuality perspective.

dark side doesn't have to be associated with bad things. view it  as her subconscious, her mind is water, her subconscious is deep sea and the deeper under the water you go the darker it is.

it isn't just about the sex, remember it's about being the man that she can be most vulnerable with. it's about being the man that can heal her, help her grow and evolve in many areas. since many men are not able to get a woman to that place many women will never come across men they can drop their mask around.

listen to this clip and peep the part about the woman having built up things in her life that she needs to get off. he is the type of dude women feel comfortable opening up and being vulnerable with.

this doesn't mean he is her dark side lover sexually, but he is definitely speaking as a dark side lover from the non sexual aspect. a man can be the non sexual dark side guy to a woman, without her even having sex with him. so the non sexual and sexual dark side man are separate from each other.

a woman can drop her mask and tell you all her vulnerable stories about her life, without divulging she likes to be pissed on and put on a leash.

it is always a give and take though. she gains by finally being able to release cuz she is with a man she can drop her mask with completely. imagine having to wear makeup and a costume every time you stepped out of your house. wouldn't it be a release to be able to just walk out without the extra stuff. women even feel this way about makeup, you use so much makeup for years and years it gets to point where you skin has been destroyed now you must wear the mask just to look pretty.

many men and women will never be able to be a dark side to their partner and that is why you have high value and you are the prize.

you should feel bad for the woman when she rejects you or doesn't recognize your value, cuz she will forever be on the conveyor belt of mediocrity, heading down a path of confusion without ever evolving, lacking a proper man to lead and teach her.

what we wear is not consent!

2. join us on 26th november between 10-12 in a central london location (tbc) either in your underwear or wearing it over your clothes.

3. tell everyone you know to join in!
